Trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed and halved lengthways) then halve lengthways.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed and quartered lengthways, chopped into small pieces).

Halve the @lime{1}(halved).

Thinly slice the @chilli{1}(thinly sliced).

Place a #large pot{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, add the @prawns{180%g} and carrot.

Fry until prawns are cooked and carrot is softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. Prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Add the @Thai style spice mix{2%sachets} and @korma curry paste{1%sachet} and cook for ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{1%pack}, @vegetable stock{1%sachet} and @water{300%ml} (double for 4p).

Bring to the boil, cover and simmer for ~{8-10%minutes}.

While the laksa simmers, place a #pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.

Once hot, lay in the pak choi. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Cook on one side for ~{2%minutes} then turn over and cook for another ~{2%minutes}.

Add the garlic to the pak choi and fry for ~{1%minute}. It should be slightly browned and charred.

Add a splash of @water{to taste}, pop a #lid{} (or some #foil{}) on the pan and leave to steam for another ~{3%minutes}.

When the laksa has 1 min of cooking time remaining, add the @udon noodles{300%g}.

Stir carefully to separate the noodles and allow them to warm through.

Season to taste with salt, pepper and a squeeze of lime juice.

Divide the prawn laksa between #bowls{}.

Top with garlic pak choi and sliced chilli (use less if you don't like spice).

Cut any remaining lime into wedges and serve alongside.